1
00:00:06,410 --> 00:00:08,192
So, interviews are split, thank you.

2
00:00:08,192 --> 00:00:09,973
That's it, I'm done, mic drop.

3
00:00:09,973 --> 00:00:14,937
Interviews, I think, are generally split into two sort of things.

4
00:00:14,937 --> 00:00:16,799
There's two major things that you're looking for.

5
00:00:16,799 --> 00:00:18,520
The first is the technical side,

6
00:00:18,520 --> 00:00:22,123
the second is more of the personality, do they fit into the culture side.

7
00:00:22,123 --> 00:00:23,544
So, I'm going to be focusing on the tech,

8
00:00:23,544 --> 00:00:26,306
and Brian's going to focus on the other stuff.

9
00:00:26,727 --> 00:00:27,828
So it's hard, right?

10
00:00:27,828 --> 00:00:32,092
Interviews are super hard to be in and to give.

11
00:00:32,092 --> 00:00:33,814
You're in this panel of people trying

12
00:00:33,814 --> 00:00:36,016
to decide within just a few hours,

13
00:00:36,016 --> 00:00:39,099
is this person the right person for our team?

14
00:00:39,099 --> 00:00:41,902
Can this person do the technical stuff that we want, right?

15
00:00:41,902 --> 00:00:42,263
It's hard.

16
00:00:42,263 --> 00:00:44,765
And programming is a very time-intensive task.

17
00:00:45,547 --> 00:00:48,410
So it's how can you really tell in just a few hours

18
00:00:48,410 --> 00:00:50,552
what, how someone's really worth

19
00:00:50,552 --> 00:00:52,054
when it could take weeks for them

20
00:00:52,054 --> 00:00:54,856
to even spin up totally on your processes.

21
00:00:54,856 --> 00:00:55,918
Plus, I mean, you're super,

22
00:00:55,918 --> 00:00:58,701
a lot of people get super nervous in these interviews.

23
00:00:58,701 --> 00:01:00,863
So it's sitting there going, oh God.

24
00:01:00,863 --> 00:01:03,285
And so how do you try and ignore some of that stuff?

25
00:01:03,285 --> 00:01:05,668
Well, I think it starts with the big question

26
00:01:05,668 --> 00:01:07,670
of what are we even testing for?

27
00:01:08,621 --> 00:01:10,302
So for me, there are three things that I care about

28
00:01:10,302 --> 00:01:11,583
when I'm dealing with interviews.

29
00:01:11,583 --> 00:01:14,164
The first is, can they write usable code?

30
00:01:14,164 --> 00:01:15,545
Can they write code that I can use

31
00:01:15,545 --> 00:01:16,466
and ship and send somewhere?

32
00:01:17,127 --> 00:01:24,392
What are their knowledge of just CS, computer science concepts, as well as programming and

33
00:01:24,392 --> 00:01:26,774
general like AI and all that kind of stuff.

34
00:01:26,774 --> 00:01:28,916
And finally, can they iterate?

35
00:01:28,916 --> 00:01:30,717
So basically it boils down to, can you do the thing?

36
00:01:30,717 --> 00:01:31,998
Do you know about the thing?

37
00:01:31,998 --> 00:01:33,799
And can you handle someone constantly changing the thing?

38
00:01:33,799 --> 00:01:37,942
Those are the three major sort of things that I try and search for.

39
00:01:39,458 --> 00:01:42,159
And I do this with a, there's three sections

40
00:01:42,159 --> 00:01:43,859
of a typical interview that I tend to go through.

41
00:01:43,859 --> 00:01:46,580
There's a phone screen, there's a programming test,

42
00:01:46,580 --> 00:01:47,960
and then there's an in-person interview.

43
00:01:47,960 --> 00:01:49,680
And so I'll start with the programming test,

44
00:01:49,680 --> 00:01:51,381
which is can you write usable code?

45
00:01:51,381 --> 00:01:55,181
So the programming test basically is a simple take-home test.

46
00:01:55,181 --> 00:01:58,562
It allows them to work in their own environment.

47
00:01:58,562 --> 00:02:00,263
It allows them to, they can use Visual Studio

48
00:02:00,263 --> 00:02:01,563
with whatever settings they want.

49
00:02:01,563 --> 00:02:02,923
They can do anything.

50
00:02:02,923 --> 00:02:03,503
They're in a,

51
00:02:04,204 --> 00:02:06,329
a more calm environment than if I was sitting

52
00:02:06,329 --> 00:02:09,395
here with my arms folded staring at them.

53
00:02:09,395 --> 00:02:11,880
You give them some simple framework, SDL or whatever,

54
00:02:11,880 --> 00:02:13,644
and I just tell them, get this working.

55
00:02:15,847 --> 00:02:18,208
It's usually triangles, some squares, stuff like that.

56
00:02:18,208 --> 00:02:19,889
Then I hand them a game design and say, here you go.

57
00:02:19,889 --> 00:02:22,829
Make this, you have four hours, make this thing.

58
00:02:22,829 --> 00:02:25,310
Treat it as if this is shipping code.

59
00:02:25,310 --> 00:02:28,271
And so all of the stuff that's gonna be on this test

60
00:02:28,271 --> 00:02:29,851
are the things that I actually care

61
00:02:29,851 --> 00:02:31,872
that they know how to write code for.

62
00:02:31,872 --> 00:02:35,573
Usually there's some math stuff on there, some AI stuff.

63
00:02:36,573 --> 00:02:39,914
And I make them, I want to see what kind of technical decisions that they make.

64
00:02:39,914 --> 00:02:42,336
I want to see what data structure did you choose.

65
00:02:42,336 --> 00:02:44,797
A common thing that I ask for is collision detection.

66
00:02:44,797 --> 00:02:49,259
Did you just do the n-squared method or did you do some spatial partitioning or something

67
00:02:49,259 --> 00:02:50,359
a little more fancy?

68
00:02:50,359 --> 00:02:51,459
Where did you spend your time?

69
00:02:51,459 --> 00:02:53,480
And all of that.

70
00:02:53,480 --> 00:02:57,082
So it gives us a context to really start some conversation.

71
00:02:57,702 --> 00:03:00,044
When I bring them in for the in-person interview,

72
00:03:00,044 --> 00:03:01,806
if I bring them in, then that's usually

73
00:03:01,806 --> 00:03:03,508
the very first thing that we talk about.

74
00:03:03,508 --> 00:03:05,770
Here's the code that you gave us. Let's talk about these things.

75
00:03:05,770 --> 00:03:08,433
Why did you make this decision? Why did you make that decision?

76
00:03:08,433 --> 00:03:12,597
So the major things that I look for are consistency.

77
00:03:12,597 --> 00:03:14,178
I don't care what your coding style is,

78
00:03:14,178 --> 00:03:16,000
but one thing I think hopefully we can all agree on

79
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:18,482
is that whatever your coding style is, it should be consistent.

80
00:03:19,318 --> 00:03:20,999
I look for readability and maintainability.

81
00:03:20,999 --> 00:03:22,700
Can I actually read your code?

82
00:03:22,700 --> 00:03:25,102
Or using a lot of just single letter variable names

83
00:03:25,102 --> 00:03:26,443
and that kind of stuff.

84
00:03:26,443 --> 00:03:29,424
Maintainability, can I, if this was a system

85
00:03:29,424 --> 00:03:31,966
that you wrote in a game that I'm having you work on,

86
00:03:31,966 --> 00:03:33,887
can I go in there and make changes as well?

87
00:03:34,668 --> 00:03:36,089
just good technical choices,

88
00:03:36,089 --> 00:03:37,870
did you make reasonable data structure choices,

89
00:03:37,870 --> 00:03:39,131
algorithm choices, that kind of stuff,

90
00:03:39,131 --> 00:03:40,592
and scalability.

91
00:03:40,592 --> 00:03:45,136
If I say, hey, what if we take these five agents

92
00:03:45,136 --> 00:03:46,597
that are running around that I had you build

93
00:03:46,597 --> 00:03:48,218
and now we wanna make it 5,000 agents?

94
00:03:48,218 --> 00:03:49,679
How would we change that?

95
00:03:49,679 --> 00:03:52,041
So again, this gives us a context for conversation

96
00:03:52,041 --> 00:03:54,883
and gives me a view into how they write code

97
00:03:54,883 --> 00:03:59,626
and what they should consider a production environment.

98
00:04:00,608 --> 00:04:02,090
So that's the programming test.

99
00:04:02,090 --> 00:04:03,352
And that's how I determine whether or not

100
00:04:03,352 --> 00:04:04,093
they can write usable code.

101
00:04:04,093 --> 00:04:06,777
So I think things like whiteboard questions

102
00:04:06,777 --> 00:04:07,357
and stuff like that,

103
00:04:07,357 --> 00:04:08,639
where you're sitting in front of a whiteboard

104
00:04:08,639 --> 00:04:11,243
and it's like, write a binary search on a whiteboard

105
00:04:11,243 --> 00:04:12,525
with all of us staring at you.

106
00:04:12,525 --> 00:04:13,145
That's useless.

107
00:04:13,145 --> 00:04:14,848
I don't know what that's really gonna tell you.

108
00:04:14,848 --> 00:04:16,190
If that's super important to you,

109
00:04:16,190 --> 00:04:17,532
have them do it in the programming test.

110
00:04:19,310 --> 00:04:21,071
The next step is CS Concepts.

111
00:04:21,071 --> 00:04:22,592
So I do this partially in the phone screen

112
00:04:22,592 --> 00:04:23,933
and partially in the in-person interview.

113
00:04:23,933 --> 00:04:26,355
My easiest questions and stuff are on the phone screen

114
00:04:26,355 --> 00:04:29,618
because we're just gonna end the conversation

115
00:04:29,618 --> 00:04:31,639
if you can't pass some of these tests.

116
00:04:31,639 --> 00:04:33,581
And I'll start with my very first question.

117
00:04:33,581 --> 00:04:35,763
I always ask this question, every interview in Canada.

118
00:04:35,763 --> 00:04:37,444
So if any of you happen to interview with me,

119
00:04:37,444 --> 00:04:38,285
you'll get this question too.

120
00:04:38,285 --> 00:04:40,707
So I guess you get a little bit of an inside track.

121
00:04:40,707 --> 00:04:41,467
And here it is.

122
00:04:41,467 --> 00:04:42,728
Ready?

123
00:04:43,913 --> 00:04:45,896
What is the difference between an array and a linked list?

124
00:04:45,896 --> 00:04:47,317
And why would I use one over the other?

125
00:04:47,317 --> 00:04:48,879
That's my very first question.

126
00:04:48,879 --> 00:04:50,781
And here's the crazy thing about this question.

127
00:04:50,781 --> 00:04:52,744
I would say about 50% of entry-level candidates fail

128
00:04:52,744 --> 00:04:55,507
this question, which is alarming to me.

129
00:04:55,507 --> 00:04:57,649
About 10% of experienced candidates fail this question,

130
00:04:57,649 --> 00:05:01,514
which is equally alarming to me.

131
00:05:01,514 --> 00:05:03,596
I like this question because it's

132
00:05:04,092 --> 00:05:07,433
it gives me a bit of a view into how they think about things.

133
00:05:07,433 --> 00:05:09,955
So for a new person, new engineer, just out of college,

134
00:05:09,955 --> 00:05:11,555
I expect the asymptotic answer.

135
00:05:11,555 --> 00:05:14,177
I expect, oh, I can index into an array in constant time.

136
00:05:14,177 --> 00:05:16,458
But if I try and find the nth element of a linked list,

137
00:05:16,458 --> 00:05:17,358
it's big O of n, and so on.

138
00:05:17,358 --> 00:05:19,500
I expect those types of responses.

139
00:05:19,500 --> 00:05:21,541
Whereas a more experienced engineer,

140
00:05:21,541 --> 00:05:24,522
I expect things like, well, an array is much more cache

141
00:05:24,522 --> 00:05:25,423
friendly, for instance.

142
00:05:25,423 --> 00:05:27,404
Whereas a linked list implemented with just node,

143
00:05:27,404 --> 00:05:29,725
node, node, node, well, that's all over memory.

144
00:05:30,565 --> 00:05:33,566
by by cache. And then of course we ask the questions like,

145
00:05:33,566 --> 00:05:35,287
hey, how can you solve for that kind of stuff?

146
00:05:35,287 --> 00:05:37,047
What happens if you bring a linked list into an

147
00:05:37,047 --> 00:05:38,408
array and so on.

148
00:05:38,408 --> 00:05:41,469
So I start with this question, and I build

149
00:05:41,469 --> 00:05:44,129
from that question to other questions. Then from there

150
00:05:44,129 --> 00:05:46,070
you ask the questions that are, that are interesting,

151
00:05:46,070 --> 00:05:49,131
right. Data structures, so like hash tables, trees, graphs. What

152
00:05:49,131 --> 00:05:51,071
are these things? Why would I use these things?

153
00:05:51,652 --> 00:05:53,332
And in the in-person or phone interview,

154
00:05:53,332 --> 00:05:55,812
I'm never making them actually write code.

155
00:05:55,812 --> 00:05:58,073
I'm making them, why would I use these things?

156
00:05:58,073 --> 00:05:59,293
What are these concepts?

157
00:05:59,293 --> 00:06:01,053
Breadth-first search, depth-first search, Dijkstra.

158
00:06:01,053 --> 00:06:04,894
These tools that we tend to use, why would I use this stuff?

159
00:06:04,894 --> 00:06:06,654
What's the difference between breadth-first and depth-first?

160
00:06:06,654 --> 00:06:08,735
Here's a graph on a board.

161
00:06:08,735 --> 00:06:13,296
Draw for me what the node expansion would look like.

162
00:06:13,296 --> 00:06:16,136
And AI concepts, A star, utility theory, behavior trees,

163
00:06:16,136 --> 00:06:16,836
that kind of stuff.

164
00:06:18,808 --> 00:06:20,630
One of my other very favorite questions,

165
00:06:20,630 --> 00:06:24,094
which I'll also give you, is describe a use for A star

166
00:06:24,094 --> 00:06:25,516
other than pathfinding.

167
00:06:25,516 --> 00:06:28,859
Do they know that A star is not just a pathfinding algorithm,

168
00:06:28,859 --> 00:06:30,922
right, it's a graph search, it's a generic graph search.

169
00:06:30,922 --> 00:06:33,965
You need some kind of source, some kind of destination,

170
00:06:33,965 --> 00:06:35,948
some kind of heuristic that can get me there,

171
00:06:35,948 --> 00:06:36,929
that can estimate.

172
00:06:36,929 --> 00:06:37,029
Cool.

173
00:06:39,647 --> 00:06:42,289
So these are conceptual questions.

174
00:06:42,289 --> 00:06:43,670
These are not implementation questions.

175
00:06:43,670 --> 00:06:45,831
These are why would I use this thing, right?

176
00:06:45,831 --> 00:06:47,192
When should I apply this thing?

177
00:06:47,192 --> 00:06:48,253
Have you heard of this thing?

178
00:06:48,253 --> 00:06:51,855
These are not questions that are deep, technical,

179
00:06:51,855 --> 00:06:53,196
like write the code for this.

180
00:06:53,196 --> 00:06:55,858
Because if they're sitting there in front of this panel,

181
00:06:55,858 --> 00:06:58,239
that's not gonna simulate what they're actually

182
00:06:58,239 --> 00:06:59,120
gonna be doing in real life.

183
00:06:59,120 --> 00:07:00,541
That's for the programming test.

184
00:07:00,541 --> 00:07:02,422
Leave all that stuff on the programming test.

185
00:07:02,422 --> 00:07:05,364
That if it's super important to you that they do that.

186
00:07:07,874 --> 00:07:10,756
So the next thing I want to talk about is the iteration side of things.

187
00:07:10,756 --> 00:07:11,897
This is the third thing.

188
00:07:11,897 --> 00:07:16,340
So iteration is, games are incredibly iterative.

189
00:07:16,340 --> 00:07:19,223
That's, it feels like that's all that we do is iterate, right?

190
00:07:19,223 --> 00:07:22,365
The Sims 4 AI is something like 10,000 lines of code.

191
00:07:22,365 --> 00:07:26,808
So if I just took that code right now and just typed it in,

192
00:07:26,808 --> 00:07:28,069
that's not going to take very much time.

193
00:07:28,069 --> 00:07:30,391
It's the iterations, the two years of iteration

194
00:07:30,391 --> 00:07:32,693
that we spend over and over and over and over.

195
00:07:32,693 --> 00:07:35,855
How many times have I rewritten that freaking formula?

196
00:07:35,855 --> 00:07:37,456
Just to make it feel right.

197
00:07:38,532 --> 00:07:40,213
So iteration, it's important.

198
00:07:40,213 --> 00:07:42,874
So usually what I do is I show them some kind of architecture.

199
00:07:42,874 --> 00:07:43,714
Here's my AI architecture.

200
00:07:43,714 --> 00:07:46,456
I describe it to them and I say, what do you like

201
00:07:46,456 --> 00:07:50,318
and what do you not like about this cool AI architecture?

202
00:07:50,318 --> 00:07:53,340
Then I just start throwing everything I possibly can at it.

203
00:07:53,340 --> 00:07:57,682
Basically, I play the world's shittiest designer.

204
00:07:57,682 --> 00:07:59,563
So I gave them this architecture,

205
00:07:59,563 --> 00:08:01,364
and I try and break it in every possible way

206
00:08:01,364 --> 00:08:03,645
that I can to see how do you handle

207
00:08:03,645 --> 00:08:06,587
not only the failure of breaking this architecture,

208
00:08:06,587 --> 00:08:08,208
of your architecture starting to fall apart.

209
00:08:08,508 --> 00:08:10,289
But how do you handle me as a designer making

210
00:08:10,289 --> 00:08:12,010
all these design changes?

211
00:08:12,010 --> 00:08:13,431
Because again, that's life, right?

212
00:08:13,431 --> 00:08:14,672
A designer is going to come and say, you know,

213
00:08:14,672 --> 00:08:15,753
I really like this.

214
00:08:15,753 --> 00:08:17,434
But I think we should change it to do this.

215
00:08:17,434 --> 00:08:17,994
How easy is that?

216
00:08:17,994 --> 00:08:18,995
How hard is that?

217
00:08:18,995 --> 00:08:22,417
How easily can I make relatively large,

218
00:08:22,417 --> 00:08:23,738
from a behavioral point of view, changes?

219
00:08:23,738 --> 00:08:26,740
And so either they're going to handle it or they can't.

220
00:08:26,740 --> 00:08:28,121
They're going to be the board cube on the left,

221
00:08:28,121 --> 00:08:29,902
and they're going to be perfectly fine.

222
00:08:29,902 --> 00:08:32,404
Or they're going to fall apart completely on the right.

223
00:08:32,404 --> 00:08:33,084
So that's what I do.

224
00:08:33,084 --> 00:08:37,367
I spend those are the three main pillars of things

225
00:08:37,367 --> 00:08:37,968
that I look for.

226
00:08:39,595 --> 00:08:42,736
Now, I want to talk about interviewing anti-patterns.

227
00:08:42,736 --> 00:08:43,856
That's the next big thing.

228
00:08:43,856 --> 00:08:45,357
Interviewing anti-patterns.

229
00:08:45,357 --> 00:08:49,538
So these are the types of things that I've done.

230
00:08:49,538 --> 00:08:50,958
I think probably all of us have done this.

231
00:08:50,958 --> 00:08:52,339
And certainly all of us have been in these

232
00:08:52,339 --> 00:08:53,559
types of interviews.

233
00:08:53,559 --> 00:08:56,100
And I've found that they've provided basically no utility

234
00:08:56,100 --> 00:08:57,600
in terms of whether or not this person's going to be a

235
00:08:57,600 --> 00:08:58,060
good engineer.

236
00:08:58,060 --> 00:09:02,942
So the first one is questions that test whether or not

237
00:09:02,942 --> 00:09:04,502
you've gotten this question before.

238
00:09:04,502 --> 00:09:06,563
This is one of my favorites.

239
00:09:06,563 --> 00:09:07,023
Oh, God.

240
00:09:07,023 --> 00:09:07,143
OK.

241
00:09:08,665 --> 00:09:12,172
This is one of my favorites, and I've gotten this twice now, at least two or three times now.

242
00:09:12,172 --> 00:09:15,157
And I, I have people ask this question quite a bit. Here it is.

243
00:09:15,157 --> 00:09:16,620
Detecting cycles in a linked list.

244
00:09:16,620 --> 00:09:17,682
This question.

245
00:09:18,837 --> 00:09:21,419
Right, we all know it's Floyd's cycle finding algorithm, right?

246
00:09:21,419 --> 00:09:24,341
It's the two, it's the two pointers that sort of race each other.

247
00:09:24,341 --> 00:09:28,585
Like, there's a, there's a, a constant time memory solution for this.

248
00:09:28,585 --> 00:09:31,427
But here's the thing, like, what are you really testing for here?

249
00:09:31,427 --> 00:09:33,849
Right, linked lists were invented as a thing in somewhere around 55, 56,

250
00:09:33,849 --> 00:09:36,891
and Floyd's algorithm was invented sometime in 67.

251
00:09:36,891 --> 00:09:40,094
Like, really? You're gonna expect somebody who has never heard of any of this stuff

252
00:09:40,094 --> 00:09:42,596
to find something what took us over a decade to figure out.

253
00:09:42,596 --> 00:09:45,238
That's, I don't know what you're really testing for here

254
00:09:45,238 --> 00:09:46,979
when you're doing this kind of stuff.

