00:10:37,507 --> 00:10:38,648
What does it actually do?

282
00:10:38,648 --> 00:10:40,930
What are the various tuning values for it, and so on.

283
00:10:40,930 --> 00:10:43,993
So having somebody explain the purpose of these formulas,

284
00:10:43,993 --> 00:10:46,155
great, anything I can look up in two seconds,

285
00:10:46,155 --> 00:10:46,655
what's the point?

286
00:10:46,655 --> 00:10:47,936
They'll just look it up.

287
00:10:47,936 --> 00:10:49,478
In a real, in the real world environment,

288
00:10:49,478 --> 00:10:51,059
they're just gonna look that stuff up, and they should.

289
00:10:52,060 --> 00:10:56,022
Again, the exceptions are if you need an expert in that particular thing.

290
00:10:56,022 --> 00:10:59,443
So if you're working on a Unity game and you need someone who has really deep knowledge

291
00:10:59,443 --> 00:11:00,063
of Unity, great.

292
00:11:00,063 --> 00:11:01,604
Ask all of the Unity questions you want.

293
00:11:01,604 --> 00:11:03,825
Okay, esoteric language questions.

294
00:11:03,825 --> 00:11:06,946
This is basically the same type of thing.

295
00:11:06,946 --> 00:11:12,609
So these are like language, like deep, deep language questions that, does it really matter?

296
00:11:13,330 --> 00:11:15,531
I mean, I can tell you I learned C sharp

297
00:11:15,531 --> 00:11:18,311
because I got hired on The Sims Medieval, which used C sharp.

298
00:11:18,311 --> 00:11:20,332
I learned Python, that I know Python,

299
00:11:20,332 --> 00:11:22,352
because I got hired on The Sims 4 that used Python.

300
00:11:22,352 --> 00:11:25,312
That's how I've learned, with the exception of C++

301
00:11:25,312 --> 00:11:27,373
and x86 Assembler, that's the only,

302
00:11:27,373 --> 00:11:32,054
I've only learned languages because I've been hired

303
00:11:32,054 --> 00:11:33,554
on a project that used them.

304
00:11:33,554 --> 00:11:35,974
So, unless you want a language expert,

305
00:11:35,974 --> 00:11:38,075
or they have it on their resume and there's gotchas,

306
00:11:38,075 --> 00:11:40,615
for instance, Lua's one-indexed arrays, thank you,

307
00:11:41,215 --> 00:11:45,657
Then I don't think that it's useful to ask these types of questions at all.

308
00:11:45,657 --> 00:11:47,258
I don't know what it's really going to get you.

309
00:11:47,258 --> 00:11:50,979
Again, if you're hiring an expert, all language questions are fair game.

310
00:11:50,979 --> 00:11:51,019
OK.

311
00:11:51,019 --> 00:11:53,380
Finally, clever puzzle questions.

312
00:11:53,380 --> 00:11:56,161
Right? These are like, why are manhole covers round?

313
00:11:56,161 --> 00:11:58,222
How many gas stations are there in San Francisco?

314
00:11:58,222 --> 00:12:01,143
And this is maybe where I'm going to get the most pushback.

315
00:12:01,972 --> 00:12:05,235
These types of questions, I get why they're asked.

316
00:12:05,235 --> 00:12:09,178
Right, so like how many gas stations are in San Francisco?

317
00:12:09,178 --> 00:12:11,060
Or I think the original one was in Seattle,

318
00:12:11,060 --> 00:12:12,361
because I think it was a Microsoft question.

319
00:12:12,361 --> 00:12:16,685
So this question is basically asked to see

320
00:12:16,685 --> 00:12:19,928
how do you think about this sort of super abstract problem?

321
00:12:19,928 --> 00:12:21,289
But I think there are better ways

322
00:12:21,289 --> 00:12:23,832
to handle these types of questions, right?

323
00:12:26,206 --> 00:12:29,467
For example, one of my co-workers, Peter Ingerbretson,

324
00:12:29,467 --> 00:12:31,028
who I did a lot of these interviews with

325
00:12:31,028 --> 00:12:33,949
when I was at Maxis, he has a famous question,

326
00:12:33,949 --> 00:12:35,710
which is his sock question.

327
00:12:35,710 --> 00:12:37,691
And he starts it off, prefaces it with,

328
00:12:37,691 --> 00:12:40,292
this is not a trick question.

329
00:12:40,292 --> 00:12:42,933
How do you sort your socks when you first wake up?

330
00:12:42,933 --> 00:12:44,974
Or when you first get them from the dryer?

331
00:12:45,534 --> 00:12:49,096
And then goes into more questions beyond that.

332
00:12:49,096 --> 00:12:50,997
So you can make these types of questions work,

333
00:12:50,997 --> 00:12:53,137
but just asking them open-ended abstractly,

334
00:12:53,137 --> 00:12:53,998
I don't think buys you anything.

335
00:12:53,998 --> 00:12:55,619
OK, real fast, the conclusion.

336
00:12:55,619 --> 00:12:58,540
Use programming tests to gauge their ability to write code.

337
00:12:58,540 --> 00:13:01,941
The in-person interview should be about high-level CS concepts,

338
00:13:01,941 --> 00:13:04,362
AI concepts, that kind of stuff, iteration ability,

339
00:13:04,362 --> 00:13:07,564
and please avoid those four anti-patterns that I created.

340
00:13:07,564 --> 00:13:09,245
And this is Brian.

341
00:13:09,245 --> 00:13:09,645
Thank you.

342
00:13:09,645 --> 00:13:09,845
Thank you.

343
00:13:09,845 --> 00:13:10,085
Thank you.

344
00:13:10,085 --> 00:13:10,305
Thank you.

345
00:13:10,305 --> 00:13:14,187
Thank you.

346
00:13:14,187 --> 00:13:14,787
How much time?

347
00:13:14,787 --> 00:13:15,187
I don't know.

348
00:13:16,188 --> 00:13:17,929
All right, hi.

349
00:13:17,929 --> 00:13:22,013
So I'm gonna, I'm Brian, this is Rez.

350
00:13:22,013 --> 00:13:26,856
And you people are beautiful.

351
00:13:26,856 --> 00:13:30,079
I'm gonna be doing the other half of the talk,

352
00:13:30,079 --> 00:13:32,381
which is the more squishy side of the interview,

353
00:13:32,381 --> 00:13:34,242
where I'm gonna try and talk to people

354
00:13:34,242 --> 00:13:37,465
and find out who they are as a person,

355
00:13:37,465 --> 00:13:42,709
instead of as a coding gent or gentess.

356
00:13:42,709 --> 00:13:45,612
Jesus, what's the version of that?

357
00:13:47,223 --> 00:13:47,723
Or a lady.

358
00:13:47,723 --> 00:13:50,766
So anyways, three clowns and an AI programmer

359
00:13:50,766 --> 00:13:52,367
walk into a bar and the joke is basically,

360
00:13:52,367 --> 00:13:55,930
can you tell the difference?

361
00:13:55,930 --> 00:13:57,592
Why is hiring a great AI person hard?

362
00:13:57,592 --> 00:14:01,475
Is it literally because AI programmers are that special,

363
00:14:01,475 --> 00:14:04,337
that we're that rare, that it's just hard to find us?

364
00:14:04,337 --> 00:14:06,139
I don't think so, it's the other direction.

365
00:14:06,139 --> 00:14:09,222
It's because AI in general is a super broad subject.

366
00:14:09,222 --> 00:14:11,484
You could be talking about navigation or...

367
00:14:13,144 --> 00:14:16,826
you know, animation or cognition or decision making or,

368
00:14:16,826 --> 00:14:18,866
and I'm not even gonna get into like,

369
00:14:18,866 --> 00:14:21,387
the different genres of games have very, very deep levels

370
00:14:21,387 --> 00:14:22,628
of knowledge in each sort of thing.

371
00:14:22,628 --> 00:14:24,048
So it's a super broad subject.

372
00:14:24,048 --> 00:14:27,829
You need a lot of design sense.

373
00:14:27,829 --> 00:14:30,270
Some AI challenges have to require design changes

374
00:14:30,270 --> 00:14:31,791
in order to solve really.

375
00:14:31,791 --> 00:14:33,231
You not only have to be a computer scientist,

376
00:14:33,231 --> 00:14:34,472
you have to be a cognitive scientist.

377
00:14:34,472 --> 00:14:36,512
And so you can really understand how the brain works

378
00:14:36,512 --> 00:14:37,333
so that you can like,

379
00:14:37,930 --> 00:14:41,014
trick it better into thinking that you're making an intelligent system.

380
00:14:41,014 --> 00:14:45,418
And you need somebody who can basically talk to anybody else on the team, because a lot

381
00:14:45,418 --> 00:14:52,086
of AI systems that really, really come together well are a very hardcore gelled version of

382
00:14:52,086 --> 00:14:52,386
code art.

383
00:14:52,560 --> 00:14:55,522
audio, the whole nine yards, like coming together at one.

384
00:14:55,522 --> 00:14:59,165
And finally, you kind of have to write really high quality code because

385
00:14:59,165 --> 00:15:03,249
the AI programmers are kind of up on the top of the totem pole of the whole

386
00:15:03,249 --> 00:15:06,592
code stack. And so, if somebody throws a bad animation in there,

387
00:15:06,592 --> 00:15:09,794
the AI is broke. If somebody puts some bad markup data in a level,

388
00:15:09,794 --> 00:15:12,817
the AI is broke. And if you don't write high quality code,

389
00:15:13,469 --> 00:15:16,472
they're going to actually think the AI is broke over and over and over again.

390
00:15:16,472 --> 00:15:22,378
Whereas if you can get your code good high quality and then make good debug systems,

391
00:15:22,378 --> 00:15:26,362
you can actually start having the rest of the people in the totem pole debug their stuff

392
00:15:26,362 --> 00:15:31,106
instead of always just basically assuming it's your stuff.

393
00:15:31,106 --> 00:15:31,887
So it's a hard problem.

394
00:15:32,739 --> 00:15:34,821
So you're going to interview somebody.

395
00:15:34,821 --> 00:15:36,422
Be prepared is my first thing.

396
00:15:36,422 --> 00:15:38,184
A candidate's going to come in.

397
00:15:38,184 --> 00:15:40,126
They're going to want to have a lot of questions

398
00:15:40,126 --> 00:15:41,767
about what kind of genre you're working on,

399
00:15:41,767 --> 00:15:43,889
what the team size is, what kind of autonomy

400
00:15:43,889 --> 00:15:46,331
they can prepare for, all of this.

401
00:15:46,331 --> 00:15:48,353
Sorry about the little purple thing.

402
00:15:48,353 --> 00:15:50,215
That's a little scene in a sec.

403
00:15:51,484 --> 00:15:54,986
And then the other thing you should also do is not only know all this stuff about your game,

404
00:15:54,986 --> 00:15:57,688
you should actually look at the person's resume ahead of time.

405
00:15:57,688 --> 00:16:00,230
Most people don't do this. I have no idea why.

406
00:16:00,230 --> 00:16:04,713
This is actually some random candidate's resume. I don't know who this is.

407
00:16:04,713 --> 00:16:06,434
It's mine.

408
00:16:07,782 --> 00:16:12,065
I usually just go through it and do some quick check boxes so that I know things that I want

409
00:16:12,065 --> 00:16:15,086
to ask them about, like what projects they've worked on in the past.

410
00:16:15,086 --> 00:16:18,788
I want to quickly skim through and see what their role progression has been over the course

411
00:16:18,788 --> 00:16:19,769
of their career.

412
00:16:19,769 --> 00:16:25,572
Usually, what I'm looking for is discontinuity in the graph of their things.

413
00:16:25,572 --> 00:16:30,274
So if they go from college to CTO back to janitor, I kind of want to ask them about

414
00:16:30,274 --> 00:16:30,474
that.

415
00:16:30,474 --> 00:16:31,555
That might be a good thing or bad.

416
00:16:31,555 --> 00:16:32,075
I don't know.

417
00:16:32,435 --> 00:16:34,436
And then finally I quickly scan through

418
00:16:34,436 --> 00:16:36,877
and find other words that I don't see in a lot of resumes

419
00:16:36,877 --> 00:16:39,117
like this particular person published a book

420
00:16:39,117 --> 00:16:42,238
and he also has led teams and he's also done design work.

421
00:16:42,238 --> 00:16:44,459
So I'm gonna ask about that

422
00:16:44,459 --> 00:16:46,179
when I get into the room with them.

423
00:16:46,179 --> 00:16:49,040
Don't read their damn resume in front of them.

424
00:16:49,040 --> 00:16:50,581
It takes up a lot of time

425
00:16:50,581 --> 00:16:53,402
and it shows a lot of disrespect.

426
00:16:53,402 --> 00:16:55,002
You don't have much time with a person

427
00:16:55,002 --> 00:16:56,802
and we're trying to find,

428
00:16:56,802 --> 00:17:00,484
we're trying to find out a lot about this person

429
00:17:00,484 --> 00:17:01,684
in a very short period of time.

430
00:17:02,689 --> 00:17:07,491
And I don't have really cool ways that you supposedly went to college for to do it

431
00:17:07,491 --> 00:17:10,173
when I'm talking about these more soft human skills instead.

432
00:17:10,173 --> 00:17:17,296
So, get in the room, and the first thing, like Rez was saying, is determine their nervousness level.

433
00:17:18,952 --> 00:17:20,573
Again, we have a very short time,

434
00:17:20,573 --> 00:17:22,334
and I need to break that down really, really fast,

435
00:17:22,334 --> 00:17:24,656
because I'm gonna ask you to confide a lot in me

436
00:17:24,656 --> 00:17:26,977
over the next hour, let's say.

437
00:17:26,977 --> 00:17:30,600
And so one of the things I've determined, actually,

438
00:17:30,600 --> 00:17:32,341
with personality, because I'm not gonna have them

439
00:17:32,341 --> 00:17:34,262
do whiteboard tests, I'm not gonna have them do,

440
00:17:34,262 --> 00:17:35,643
is if they're really, really super nervous,

441
00:17:35,643 --> 00:17:36,844
I'll just say, hey, do you wanna walk?

442
00:17:36,844 --> 00:17:38,626
The little bit of physical activity

443
00:17:38,626 --> 00:17:41,187
actually sucks the nervous energy right out of them.

444
00:17:41,187 --> 00:17:43,269
I actually had one interview where I walked in,

445
00:17:43,269 --> 00:17:45,871
it just happened to be on Halloween,

446
00:17:45,871 --> 00:17:48,052
and I came in dressed as Thor.

447
00:17:48,957 --> 00:17:50,919
and gave the interview.

448
00:17:50,919 --> 00:17:53,883
And I said, you know, I'm sorry about this afterwards.

449
00:17:53,883 --> 00:17:56,185
She goes, actually, I was super nervous,

450
00:17:56,185 --> 00:17:59,489
but then when you came and dressed as Thor,

451
00:17:59,489 --> 00:18:00,530
it just all went away.

452
00:18:00,530 --> 00:18:01,872
So now I do that all the time.

453
00:18:01,872 --> 00:18:02,332
No, I'm just kidding.

454
00:18:03,548 --> 00:18:06,309
So basically what you wanna do is quickly transition

455
00:18:06,309 --> 00:18:07,770
into a full-blown conversation.

456
00:18:07,770 --> 00:18:11,051
This should be a very pleasant conversation.

457
00:18:11,051 --> 00:18:13,032
Shakespeare is always good with the words.

458
00:18:13,032 --> 00:18:14,952
You know, try to be pleasant and witty

459
00:18:14,952 --> 00:18:16,393
and make it an open sort of notion.

460
00:18:16,393 --> 00:18:19,614
It's a very trusting environment, but it should be novel.

461
00:18:19,614 --> 00:18:22,055
If things feel too rehearsed,

462
00:18:22,055 --> 00:18:23,676
people are gonna pick up on that really quick.

463
00:18:24,612 --> 00:18:28,014
But this is where you really need to know something about yourself as an interviewer.

464
00:18:28,014 --> 00:18:31,576
If you're not the kind of person that can walk up to anybody and start a conversation,

465
00:18:31,576 --> 00:18:36,379
if you're not the kind of person that feels comfortable sharing so that they'll feel comfortable

466
00:18:36,379 --> 00:18:40,181
in return sharing, things can get really weird really fast and you don't want to do that.

467
00:18:40,181 --> 00:18:42,963
So maybe you're not the right person for this part of the interview.

468
00:18:44,315 --> 00:18:45,937
Biggest thing you want to find here is,

469
00:18:45,937 --> 00:18:48,382
does this person fit into the team?

470
00:18:48,382 --> 00:18:51,286
Is he a good ingredient in the team stew

471
00:18:51,286 --> 00:18:52,949
that you've currently got going?

472
00:18:52,949 --> 00:18:54,632
So I ask a couple of questions,

473
00:18:54,632 --> 00:18:56,475
usually about what's the worst project

474
00:18:56,475 --> 00:18:57,757
they've ever been on and the best project

475
00:18:57,757 --> 00:18:58,438
they've ever been on.

476
00:18:58,999 --> 00:19:01,800
depending on how the conversation is going so far,

477
00:19:01,800 --> 00:19:03,400
is which one I ask first, right?

478
00:19:03,400 --> 00:19:05,861
And the thing is that these actually give you

479
00:19:05,861 --> 00:19:08,241
very different notions back about the person.

480
00:19:08,241 --> 00:19:10,782
The worst job, it could be because

481
00:19:10,782 --> 00:19:12,822
the game sucked or the team sucked.

482
00:19:12,822 --> 00:19:15,803
And in either case, I wanna know if they have any notions

483
00:19:15,803 --> 00:19:16,703
as to how to fix things.

484
00:19:16,703 --> 00:19:18,683
I also wanna know how much smack they're gonna talk about

485
00:19:18,683 --> 00:19:23,244
their ex-employee or ex-peers or their employer.

486
00:19:23,244 --> 00:19:25,705
I kinda wanna get a sense of like,

487
00:19:25,705 --> 00:19:27,965
how sort of spiteful people are, if you will.

488
00:19:28,980 --> 00:19:32,863
You know, games are a high-tension environment and this is going to come up.

489
00:19:32,863 --> 00:19:36,326
I don't know that I want somebody that's going to walk around for the next 20 years telling

490
00:19:36,326 --> 00:19:39,568
everybody what a POSI is because of one thing that I made him do someday.

491
00:19:40,947 --> 00:19:45,031
I want to know if they'll take any personal responsibility for if things went bad, if

492
00:19:45,031 --> 00:19:48,554
they have any thoughts of it, or if they're the kind of person that just blames everybody

493
00:19:48,554 --> 00:19:49,374
else.

494
00:19:49,374 --> 00:19:52,017
And then finally, I have to know their pet peeves.

495
00:19:52,017 --> 00:19:55,400
Pet peeves are actually the thing that in many cases will ruin an entire project for

496
00:19:55,400 --> 00:19:55,760
people.

497
00:19:55,760 --> 00:20:00,164
It turns out that this person just absolutely can't stand being in the dark, and the whole

498
00:20:00,164 --> 00:20:01,465
team loves to have the lights out.

499
00:20:01,665 --> 00:20:04,308
and I know my team actually has the lights out

500
00:20:04,308 --> 00:20:06,089
and so if that's his pet peeve,

501
00:20:06,089 --> 00:20:07,931
it's probably not gonna work out.

502
00:20:07,931 --> 00:20:10,073
In the other direction, the best job ever

503
00:20:10,073 --> 00:20:12,355
tells me their passions and what they think,

504
00:20:12,355 --> 00:20:13,736
what's most valuable to them.

505
00:20:13,736 --> 00:20:15,638
They might actually tell me,

506
00:20:15,638 --> 00:20:17,760
I've had this multiple times where a person tells me

507
00:20:17,760 --> 00:20:19,061
that his favorite job ever.

508
00:20:19,401 --> 00:20:21,704
had constant year-long crunch,

509
00:20:21,704 --> 00:20:23,666
and he hated half the people on the team.

510
00:20:23,666 --> 00:20:25,668
But goddamn if he didn't love the game,

511
00:20:25,668 --> 00:20:27,009
and they shipped on time!

512
00:20:27,009 --> 00:20:29,572
And so like, I know exactly what that person values

513
00:20:29,572 --> 00:20:32,255
and what he's gonna overlook every other bad thing

514
00:20:32,255 --> 00:20:33,877
if he just gets that one thing, right?

515
00:20:34,812 --> 00:20:38,155
Secondly, it tells me where in the hierarchy they really want to be.

516
00:20:38,155 --> 00:20:42,277
Type A, type of very, very go-getter people

517
00:20:42,277 --> 00:20:45,680
will rarely ever tell you that their best job was whether they were a foot soldier.

518
00:20:45,680 --> 00:20:47,381
But they will tell you that, you know,

519
00:20:47,381 --> 00:20:50,563
somebody took a chance on me and gave me this huge pile of responsibility

520
00:20:50,563 --> 00:20:51,704
and it was the greatest job.

521
00:20:51,704 --> 00:20:55,086
And so now you know kind of what they think of themselves

522
00:20:55,086 --> 00:20:57,008
as far as what they're capable of

523
00:20:57,008 --> 00:20:59,469
and also where in the hierarchy they see themselves.

524
00:21:00,030 --> 00:21:05,896
Anytime you're talking about projects, though, please make sure you very explicitly ask them what it was that they did themselves.

525
00:21:05,896 --> 00:21:13,665
Otherwise, you might get a story about their favorite job, and it turns out that they were an embedded QA on it for a week, you know, 20 years ago, and they just still love that job.

526
00:21:13,665 --> 00:21:16,528
Just make sure that you find out.

527
00:21:16,528 --> 00:21:22,034
Next area I go into is I ask this question, what kind of work do you want to do here? This just gives me their expectations.

528
00:21:22,437 --> 00:21:24,477
And again, it goes back to that broad AI notion.

529
00:21:24,477 --> 00:21:27,439
I want to know if what they think of as game AI

530
00:21:27,439 --> 00:21:30,320
is what I think of as game AI.

531
00:21:30,320 --> 00:21:33,121
And I tend to just let them go on this for the longest time

532
00:21:33,121 --> 00:21:36,322
because even if they don't have a perfect fit for my team,

533
00:21:36,322 --> 00:21:38,863
there's a lot of other roles potentially in the company.

534
00:21:38,863 --> 00:21:40,824
And so I let them go as to what kind of work

535
00:21:40,824 --> 00:21:42,124
they actually want to do,

536
00:21:42,124 --> 00:21:44,726
because that role might be down the hallway.

537
00:21:44,726 --> 00:21:47,106
And so even if they don't fit specifically on my team,

538
00:21:47,106 --> 00:21:48,807
I can go get them to somebody else real quick.

539
00:21:50,909 --> 00:21:54,512
And then finally, to Rez's Microsoft questions,

540
00:21:54,512 --> 00:21:55,653
the puzzle questions.

541
00:21:55,653 --> 00:21:57,975
I don't really believe in them either

542
00:21:57,975 --> 00:21:59,636
when it comes to technical code

543
00:21:59,636 --> 00:22:01,698
or how abstract problem solving happens.

544
00:22:01,698 --> 00:22:04,260
But when it comes to getting to the deep notions

545
00:22:04,260 --> 00:22:05,501
of what personality are,

546
00:22:05,501 --> 00:22:07,803
I actually agree with personality style

547
00:22:07,803 --> 00:22:09,084
Microsoft questions, if you will.

548
00:22:09,084 --> 00:22:10,565
So I'll ask questions like,

549
00:22:10,565 --> 00:22:12,447
how often do you change the layout of your living room?

550
00:22:12,447 --> 00:22:13,948
This gives me a little bit of a notion

551
00:22:13,948 --> 00:22:15,789
as to their OCD nature,

552
00:22:15,789 --> 00:22:18,572
how much of like the control of their environment

553
00:22:18,572 --> 00:22:19,573
they kind of have.

554
00:22:19,573 --> 00:22:20,613
And to a certain extent.

555
00:22:20,853 --> 00:22:26,155
This actually has a pretty good correlation with how they feel about code refactoring.

556
00:22:26,155 --> 00:22:29,317
Do you like 20 problems or one problem with 20 parts?

557
00:22:29,317 --> 00:22:31,217
This is a sort of a question that says,

558
00:22:31,217 --> 00:22:34,418
do you mind having a bunch of tasks that could go in a million different directions,

559
00:22:34,418 --> 00:22:38,900
or do you absolutely kind of need this tethering one direction that you can always steer back towards?

560
00:22:38,900 --> 00:22:42,621
I find that people that are going to be doing prototyping enjoy more 20 problems,

561
00:22:42,621 --> 00:22:46,443
versus people that are more production-oriented want one problem with 20 parts.

562
00:22:47,879 --> 00:22:49,561
When's the last time you changed somebody's life?

563
00:22:49,561 --> 00:22:51,504
This is a sneaky way of finding out

564
00:22:51,504 --> 00:22:52,885
how good of a leader they are,

565
00:22:52,885 --> 00:22:54,287
even if they've never had a lead role.

566
00:22:54,287 --> 00:22:57,331
Sometimes it doesn't take much to change somebody's life,

567
00:22:57,331 --> 00:22:59,894
and the people that actually have cool answers

568
00:22:59,894 --> 00:23:03,378
to this question are probably good people

569
00:23:03,378 --> 00:23:04,360
that you want on your team.

570
00:23:05,716 --> 00:23:07,237
When was your favorite childhood toy?

571
00:23:07,237 --> 00:23:08,958
If you're outside playing sports

572
00:23:08,958 --> 00:23:10,778
versus inside playing with Legos

573
00:23:10,778 --> 00:23:13,240
versus you had a bunch of action figures and dolls

574
00:23:13,240 --> 00:23:14,800
and you were doing more story-based stuff,

575
00:23:14,800 --> 00:23:17,042
I wanna kinda know the deep lizard-level brain

576
00:23:17,042 --> 00:23:19,083
of what you think of as play.

577
00:23:19,083 --> 00:23:21,924
Because I know what this company thinks of as play

578
00:23:21,924 --> 00:23:23,845
and I wanna know if you're compatible with that

579
00:23:23,845 --> 00:23:26,666
and I also wanna know if the thing that really drives you

580
00:23:26,666 --> 00:23:29,368
is exploration or social dynamics

581
00:23:29,368 --> 00:23:32,149
or building, those sorts of things.

582
00:23:33,104 --> 00:23:34,746
How many books did you read last year?

583
00:23:34,746 --> 00:23:36,327
This is kind of a general one.

584
00:23:36,327 --> 00:23:39,590
I know a lot of really smart people that don't read at all,

585
00:23:39,590 --> 00:23:42,413
but everybody I know that's a voracious reader

586
00:23:42,413 --> 00:23:43,073
is really smart.

587
00:23:43,613 --> 00:23:45,934
And typically, if you're a voracious reader

588
00:23:45,934 --> 00:23:48,616
and you don't know exactly what it is that's going on,

589
00:23:48,616 --> 00:23:51,077
you'll probably go pick up a book and read about it

590
00:23:51,077 --> 00:23:52,799
and learn about it and be good.

591
00:23:52,799 --> 00:23:55,000
And if you have that voracious reading habit,

592
00:23:55,000 --> 00:23:56,361
I find that those type of people,

593
00:23:56,361 --> 00:23:59,102
especially in an environment that's a little bit chaotic,

594
00:23:59,102 --> 00:24:00,263
I don't have to worry about them as much

595
00:24:00,263 --> 00:24:03,145
because they'll just read the damn wiki or something

596
00:24:03,145 --> 00:24:04,686
and figure out how to make things happen.

597
00:24:05,639 --> 00:24:08,242
and tell me something there's no way I would ever guess about you.

598
00:24:08,242 --> 00:24:11,266
If I actually have spent some time with you and we do have some trust,

599
00:24:11,266 --> 00:24:14,490
I find this is a cool question that they'll give me an answer to

600
00:24:14,490 --> 00:24:17,874
that there's no possible way that I could ever know how to ask them.

601
00:24:17,874 --> 00:24:20,717
And so they'll give up information that's cool or deep about them

602
00:24:20,717 --> 00:24:23,460
that like I couldn't have thought otherwise.

603
00:24:24,455 --> 00:24:25,615
So then I turn it about, of course.

604
00:24:25,615 --> 00:24:28,476
I always give them, this is a conversation, right?

605
00:24:28,476 --> 00:24:30,857
So I'm always asking them questions that they can answer,

606
00:24:30,857 --> 00:24:32,918
but at the end, give them extra time.

607
00:24:32,918 --> 00:24:35,279
And now slam right up against the edge of your NDA

608
00:24:35,279 --> 00:24:37,700
because this is the place where you wanna show

609
00:24:37,700 --> 00:24:40,461
the company's flaws, you wanna say, hey, you know what?

610
00:24:40,461 --> 00:24:42,402
No place is perfect, but here's why

611
00:24:42,402 --> 00:24:43,823
working here is good anyway.

612
00:24:43,823 --> 00:24:46,284
The company is good, the project is good,

613
00:24:46,284 --> 00:24:48,625
the people are good, and therefore,

614
00:24:48,625 --> 00:24:50,385
the flaws aren't the problem.

615
00:24:51,488 --> 00:24:55,433
Also, I have a lot of excellent answers to why do you work here, because everybody asks

616
00:24:55,433 --> 00:24:56,154
this question.

617
00:24:56,154 --> 00:25:01,661
It's sort of like the easy, I'm going to ask the interviewer the question question.

618
00:25:01,661 --> 00:25:04,945
And please don't have a rehearsed answer because it comes off as very...

619
00:25:06,055 --> 00:25:11,600
It comes off as rehearsed and it's insincere.

620
00:25:11,600 --> 00:25:14,382
And again, human beings are just gloriously good

621
00:25:14,382 --> 00:25:15,864
at doing insincerity.

622
00:25:15,864 --> 00:25:18,026
And remember the doorknob questions.

623
00:25:18,026 --> 00:25:19,567
This is a medical thing.

624
00:25:19,567 --> 00:25:21,669
People will go to the doctor,

625
00:25:21,669 --> 00:25:24,231
they'll say they have something that's untoward,

626
00:25:24,231 --> 00:25:25,913
wrong with them, so they don't want to say it

627
00:25:25,913 --> 00:25:27,574
because they're embarrassed.

628
00:25:28,175 --> 00:25:30,035
They'll say, I have stomach pain and a headache,

629
00:25:30,035 --> 00:25:32,336
some generic thing, and they'll hope the doctor can find it,

630
00:25:32,336 --> 00:25:33,796
and of course, he never does.

631
00:25:33,796 --> 00:25:35,977
And then he'll go, okay, and he'll walk over to the door,

632
00:25:35,977 --> 00:25:38,418
and he'll grab the doorknob, and he'll turn around and say,

633
00:25:38,418 --> 00:25:39,578
so is there anything else?

634
00:25:39,578 --> 00:25:41,338
And there's some actual statistic

635
00:25:41,338 --> 00:25:44,559
that some large percentage of all diagnoses

636
00:25:44,559 --> 00:25:47,600
happen with the doctor's hand sitting on the doorknob

637
00:25:47,600 --> 00:25:49,281
going, are we done now?

638
00:25:49,281 --> 00:25:52,282
And that's actually right when the person says,

639
00:25:52,282 --> 00:25:54,602
oh well, I'm having, hmm, hmm, hmm, all right?

640
00:25:54,602 --> 00:25:55,883
And then that's when it comes out.

641
00:25:58,079 --> 00:26:01,109
So usually what happens at the end of the interview is I basically say,

642
00:26:01,109 --> 00:26:04,840
you know, here's my, you know, I have to go now, but here's my, my.

643
00:26:05,697 --> 00:26:08,819
my email address, an hour from now when you think of a question,

644
00:26:08,819 --> 00:26:12,141
or tonight at 3 AM when you wake up with this question in your mouth,

645
00:26:12,141 --> 00:26:14,202
please just shoot it off to me and do it.

646
00:26:14,202 --> 00:26:16,703
More times than not, that is the question.

647
00:26:16,703 --> 00:26:19,064
The answer to that question is the one that

648
00:26:19,064 --> 00:26:20,665
gets the person to actually join the company.

649
00:26:20,665 --> 00:26:23,467
That's the one that they really have a deep fear,

650
00:26:23,467 --> 00:26:25,868
or they really have and they didn't think of it on the time,

651
00:26:25,868 --> 00:26:28,910
because maybe we did have a good conversation and it took too long.

652
00:26:28,910 --> 00:26:31,531
Anyway, so that's the last part of that.

653
00:26:31,531 --> 00:26:32,952
So any questions?

654
00:26:41,124 --> 00:26:46,807
if you're right in the back with your hand on the doorknob.

655
00:26:46,807 --> 00:26:47,028
Hold on.

656
00:26:47,028 --> 00:26:49,249
Yeah, go ahead.

657
00:26:49,249 --> 00:26:50,810
We got you.

658
00:26:50,810 --> 00:26:53,892
I put my hand on the doorknob.

659
00:26:53,892 --> 00:26:55,693
He put his hand on me.

660
00:26:55,693 --> 00:26:57,814
I am apparently the doorknob.

661
00:26:57,814 --> 00:27:00,496
So, yeah, we've got two, three minutes.

662
00:27:00,496 --> 00:27:03,017
Come back up here so you're on camera when you're answering.

